Cleaning up

departments <- c("Operations", "Management", "Administration", "Sales", "Engineering")
paygap <- paygap %>% 
  mutate(dept = factor(dept, 
                       levels = departments))
educ <- c("College", "Masters", "PhD", "High School")

paygap <- paygap %>% 
  mutate(edu = factor(edu,
                      levels = educ))

paygap_clean <- paygap %>% 
  mutate(age_bin = cut(age,
                     breaks = c(0, 25, 35, 45, 55, Inf),
                     right = FALSE)) %>%
  mutate(total_pay = basePay + bonus) %>% 
  mutate_if(is_character, fct_infreq) %>%
  mutate(age_bin = fct_infreq(age_bin)) -> 
  paygap_clean

Summary Statistics

I made a new dataframe that shows the mean and median total salaries for both genders

paygap_clean %>%
  group_by(gender, edu, age_bin, dept, jobTitle) %>%
  summarise(
    mean_pay = mean(total_pay),
    median_pay = median(total_pay),
    count = n()) -> paygap_clean
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'gender', 'edu', 'age_bin', 'dept'. You can
## override using the `.groups` argument.

Viz

Pay gap on the basis of mean_pay for all occupations, education levels and ages

ggplot(paygap_clean, aes(x = gender, y = mean_pay, fill = gender))+
  geom_col() +
  labs(
    title = "Gender Pay Gap based on Mean Pay",
    x = "Gender",
    y = "Mean Pay")

#1 : Gender, Mean pay and occupation

ggplot(paygap_clean,aes(x = jobTitle, y = mean_pay, fill = gender ) ) +
  geom_col() +
  labs(
    title = "Gender Pay Gap based on Occupation",
    x = "Occupation",
    y = "Mean Pay") +
  scale_fill_manual(values = c(wes_palette("Royal1") [4], wes_palette("Royal2") [5])) +
  coord_flip()

#2 : Gender, mean pay and age

paygap_clean %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = age_bin, y = mean_pay, fill = gender ) ) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity") +
  labs(
    title = "Gender Pay Gap based on Age",
    x = "Age Bins",
    y = "Mean Pay") +
  scale_fill_manual(values = c(wes_palette("Zissou1") [1], wes_palette("Zissou1") [4]))

#3 : Gender, mean pay and education

paygap_clean %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = edu, y = mean_pay, fill = gender ) ) +
  #ggcorr(paygap_clean, label = TRUE, label_alpha = TRUE)
  geom_bar(stat = "identity") +
  labs(
    title = "Gender Pay Gap based on Education",
    x = "Education Levels",
    y = "Mean Pay") +
  scale_fill_manual(values = c(wes_palette("Zissou1") [1], wes_palette("Zissou1") [5])) +
  facet_wrap(~gender)
